snippet.textDisplay:
Cadbury makes some wonderful chocolate, or at least had done until a few years ago.
The taste has since changed a little.
I always prefer chocolate that has cocoa butter near the top of the ingredients list; certainly before cocoa mass; "roughage" or "filler" I call it.
You will have difficulty finding a milk chocolate that has cocoa butter and milk so near the top like cadbury's dairy milk.
Even much of the chocolate made by the premium brands such as lindt, fail in prioritising the quality defining components of cocoa.


It's like when I make an espresso, I drink the extraction, then I throw the spent coffee grounds in the garden for compost.
I dont make an espresso with spent coffee grounds and then add some extraction afterwards- the principle method used by supposedly premium companies.
the comment cadbury's not a "higher quality chocolate" needs some defining.

snippet.textDisplay:
I like the haircut, also I respect Claire keeping the white streak nicely parted and featured.

I agree Cadbury is likely not the best quality, but it has a huge market appeal. I don't know if their quality differs in different countries, but I know Australian Cadbury has to conform to Australian food laws about chocolate (basically, it requires certain percentages of cocoa fat).

As for Creme Eggs, I tend to avoid the original flavour because the filling is too sweet for my tastes. The Caramello one isn't bad and I have had a popping candy one as well. I just don't have them often because on a whole, Easter eggs always cost more per gram than normal chocolate blocks.
